Subject: Implement the libevdi event loop so kwin's pageflips actually complete

EVDI is a userspace-driven DRM device. Unlike a real GPU connector, a
pageflip submitted to /dev/dri/cardN (EVDI) does NOT complete until the
userspace controller (us, via libevdi) explicitly acknowledges it by:

  1. Registering a buffer via evdi_register_buffer()
  2. Arming the next frame with evdi_request_update()
  3. Polling for events with evdi_handle_events()

MrOz59's port of Apollo to Linux LOADS the libevdi function pointers
(evdi_register_buffer, evdi_request_update, evdi_grab_pixels,
 evdi_handle_events, evdi_get_event_ready) but never CALLS any of them.

The downstream effect, visible in kwin's log every second of a streaming
session:

    kwin_wayland: Pageflip timed out! This is a bug in the evdi kernel driver
    kwin_wayland: Pageflip timed out! This is a bug in the evdi kernel driver
    kwin_wayland: Pageflip timed out! This is a bug in the evdi kernel driver
    ...
    kwin_wayland: Pageflip arrived after all, 126631ms after the commit

The header is misleading: it's not a kernel-driver bug, it's that the
userspace pageflip-completion contract simply isn't being honoured.
Because kwin's pageflips never complete, kwin's render queue stalls,
no new frames reach the EVDI plane, and Apollo's KMS capture reads
the zero-initialised initial framebuffer = black screen on the Steam
Deck (audio works fine through a separate path).

This patch wires up the minimum viable libevdi event pump:

  - VirtualDisplayInfo gets a CPU buffer (width*height*4) and a
    registered-buffer id.
  - openVDisplayDevice() starts a single global event-pump thread for
    the whole process. The thread snapshots the active EVDI handles
    under vdisplay_mutex, releases the lock, then calls
    evdi_get_event_ready / evdi_handle_events / evdi_request_update on
    each handle. 5ms sleep between iterations (≈200Hz).
  - closeVDisplayDevice() joins the thread *before* taking the mutex
    (the loop acquires the mutex itself, so joining inside would
    deadlock).
  - createVirtualDisplay registers a fresh buffer with the new EVDI
    handle and arms the first request_update right after evdi_connect.
  - removeVirtualDisplay unregisters the buffer before evdi_disconnect.

We use a no-op update_ready callback because Apollo's existing KMS
capture pipeline reads kwin's GBM-allocated dma-buf (the same memory
EVDI is shadowing), so we don't need to consume the pixels via
evdi_grab_pixels — we just need the event-pump side-effects (ACK so
kwin's pageflip completes; re-arm via request_update so the next
frame fires). If a future change wants to bypass KMS and read pixels
directly, vdinfo.evdi_buf is already the destination libevdi writes
into.

End-to-end after this patch (expected):

    [VDISPLAY] Registered libevdi buffer id=1 (1280x800, 4096000 bytes); pageflips will now complete.
    [VDISPLAY] EVDI event pump thread started.
    [no more "Pageflip timed out" spam from kwin]
    [actual desktop content streams to the Steam Deck]

--- a/src/platform/linux/virtual_display.cpp
+++ b/src/platform/linux/virtual_display.cpp
@@ -30,6 +30,7 @@
 
